WEBVTT

1
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.736
This programme contains
strong language

2
00:00:05.760 --> 00:00:09.240
and scenes some viwers
may find distressing.

3
00:00:14.400 --> 00:00:15.840
Where've you been?

4
00:00:17.240 --> 00:00:19.056
Danny sent me home last night.

5
00:00:19.080 --> 00:00:21.240
I'm sorry. I thought he told you.

6
00:00:22.600 --> 00:00:24.096
OK. no problem.

7
00:00:24.120 --> 00:00:28.456
So. as you know. we've been asked
to recheck the BT malware.

8
00:00:28.480 --> 00:00:30.256
I'd like you to do a strings.

9
00:00:30.280 --> 00:00:33.576
What. just pull all the text? Yeah.

10
00:00:33.600 --> 00:00:35.176
That's right. and go through it.

11
00:00:35.200 --> 00:00:38.816
You know. passwords. hash types...

12
00:00:38.840 --> 00:00:40.136
See if we missed anything.

13
00:00:40.160 --> 00:00:43.176
Look. if this is my fault
I'm really sorry... It's fine.

14
00:00:43.200 --> 00:00:45.296
Someone needs to do the strings.

15
00:00:45.320 --> 00:00:47.096
You're here on work experience.

16
00:00:47.120 --> 00:00:49.776
Or. do you think
you're too grand to do it?

17
00:00:49.800 --> 00:00:52.216
No. of course not.

18
00:00:52.240 --> 00:00:54.016
Good.

19
00:00:54.040 --> 00:00:55.720
Well. off you go then.

20
00:01:44.520 --> 00:01:47.216
Options for an
Offensive Cyber response.

21
00:01:47.240 --> 00:01:49.096
With respect. Prime Minister.

22
00:01:49.120 --> 00:01:51.496
can I say that GCHQ opposes

23
00:01:51.520 --> 00:01:54.496
the use of OC in a situation of this kind?

24
00:01:54.520 --> 00:01:55.936
Why?

25
00:01:55.960 --> 00:01:59.536
Because of the law
of unintended consequences.

26
00:01:59.560 --> 00:02:02.336
We close down part
of Russia's electricity grid

27
00:02:02.360 --> 00:02:04.536
but it turns out it also supplies a hospital.

28
00:02:04.560 --> 00:02:06.696
They broadcast pictures of patients
dying and we've got a...

29
00:02:06.720 --> 00:02:09.736
Offensive Cyber is an attack
on a country.

30
00:02:09.760 --> 00:02:11.976
just like in any other domain of conflict.

31
00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:14.576
and it's very. very dangerous.
as. with respect.

32
00:02:14.600 --> 00:02:16.096
we are proving here.

33
00:02:16.120 --> 00:02:17.896
They take out part of our infrastructure.

34
00:02:17.920 --> 00:02:20.616
We retaliate. attack one of their systems.

35
00:02:20.640 --> 00:02:23.056
They hit us again.
this time a more critical target.

36
00:02:23.080 --> 00:02:25.696
We up the stakes another notch
and. before you know it.

37
00:02:25.720 --> 00:02:29.216
we're into a cycle of escalation
and a catastrophic loss of life.

38
00:02:29.240 --> 00:02:30.600
So. what do you suggest we do?

39
00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:34.496
Expel more diplomats.
like we did after Novichok?

40
00:02:34.520 --> 00:02:36.416
Look how much good that did.

41
00:02:36.440 --> 00:02:38.496
They're playground bullies.

42
00:02:38.520 --> 00:02:41.056
We need to hit back
in a language they understand.

43
00:02:41.080 --> 00:02:44.800
If we do nothing. they'll just
come back at us harder next time.

44
00:02:46.360 --> 00:02:47.920
Options.

45
00:02:52.480 --> 00:02:56.976
Well. we could turn off SWIFT
to all their banks.

46
00:02:57.000 --> 00:02:59.616
That might be quite appropriate.
given the impact

47
00:02:59.640 --> 00:03:01.736
of their attacks on our cash machines.

48
00:03:01.760 --> 00:03:02.760
No.

49
00:03:04.600 --> 00:03:06.056
OK. Well.

50
00:03:06.080 --> 00:03:10.496
we could take control
of Putin's car briefly.

51
00:03:10.520 --> 00:03:12.256
Flash the lights.

52
00:03:12.280 --> 00:03:14.736
accelerate and decelerate.

53
00:03:14.760 --> 00:03:15.896
that kind of thing.

54
00:03:15.920 --> 00:03:18.136
You can do that? Yes.

55
00:03:18.160 --> 00:03:23.240
We could also drop his plane
20.000 feet. mid-flight.

56
00:03:24.600 --> 00:03:27.096
As a demonstration of power.

57
00:03:27.120 --> 00:03:29.056
that might be quite effective.

58
00:03:29.080 --> 00:03:35.016
though they would almost certainly
target our leadership in response.

59
00:03:35.040 --> 00:03:36.480
No.

60
00:03:37.600 --> 00:03:38.800
What else?

61
00:03:41.640 --> 00:03:46.016
I suppose we could fry
all the lines into Glavset.

62
00:03:46.040 --> 00:03:47.216
Into what?

63
00:03:47.240 --> 00:03:48.536
Glavset.

64
00:03:48.560 --> 00:03:53.776
It's the source of most of Russia's
Twitter propaganda aimed at the UK.

65
00:03:53.800 --> 00:03:56.376
We could shut it down.

66
00:03:56.400 --> 00:03:58.816
How long would that take?

67
00:03:58.840 --> 00:04:02.976
Er. well. we'd have
to create the exploit first.

68
00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:05.296
so seven. maybe eight days.

69
00:04:05.320 --> 00:04:06.720
Eight days?

70
00:04:10.880 --> 00:04:13.400
OK. do it.

71
00:04:40.280 --> 00:04:42.376
I'm sorry. I've got to take a break.

72
00:04:42.400 --> 00:04:44.416
Can't keep my eyes open.

73
00:04:44.440 --> 00:04:46.000
OK.

74
00:04:47.560 --> 00:04:49.160
Don't be long.

75
00:05:06.680 --> 00:05:08.160
Can I...?

76
00:05:09.280 --> 00:05:11.240
Sure. why not?

77
00:05:16.920 --> 00:05:18.320
You OK?

78
00:05:20.240 --> 00:05:22.560
Just got to wake myself up.

79
00:05:26.160 --> 00:05:27.456
What is it?

80
00:05:27.480 --> 00:05:28.760
It's an energy drink.

81
00:05:34.720 --> 00:05:37.576
It's sweet.

82
00:05:37.600 --> 00:05:40.800
It's a quick hit. It'll keep you going.

83
00:05:44.760 --> 00:05:48.280
So. who is he?
The old man you keep staring at.

84
00:05:51.040 --> 00:05:52.856
Did they show you Jive?

85
00:05:52.880 --> 00:05:54.016
What?

86
00:05:54.040 --> 00:05:56.736
It's kind of like an in-house Facebook.

87
00:05:56.760 --> 00:05:59.056
Well. he writes a blog for it every week.

88
00:05:59.080 --> 00:06:01.816
correcting the grammar
in everyone else's posts.

89
00:06:01.840 --> 00:06:02.856
What?

90
00:06:02.880 --> 00:06:04.976
Yeah. No way.

91
00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:08.176
I'm not shitting you.
That's what he's doing right now.

92
00:06:08.200 --> 00:06:10.776
Just sitting there.
correcting our mistakes.

93
00:06:10.800 --> 00:06:13.320
That is one sad fucker.

94
00:06:18.040 --> 00:06:21.400
You're that student who found
the second malware. right?

95
00:06:23.080 --> 00:06:24.656
Congratulations.

96
00:06:24.680 --> 00:06:27.136
Not really.

97
00:06:27.160 --> 00:06:30.976
I thought that you were the golden girl.

98
00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:33.160
Yeah. "were" is right.

99
00:06:35.120 --> 00:06:38.536
Apparently finding that code
just made everyone else look bad.

100
00:06:38.560 --> 00:06:40.336
So now we've got to start again

101
00:06:40.360 --> 00:06:43.336
and everyone in my department
hates me.

102
00:06:43.360 --> 00:06:46.079
Well. maybe they're just jealous.

103
00:06:47.560 --> 00:06:49.120
No. really.

104
00:07:35.320 --> 00:07:36.840
What have you found?

105
00:07:41.320 --> 00:07:44.056
Some of this text is encrypted.

106
00:07:44.080 --> 00:07:47.040
That's OK. They do that sometimes.

107
00:07:51.320 --> 00:07:53.616
It's probably just a bit of random text

108
00:07:53.640 --> 00:07:55.400
that's got pasted in by mistake.

109
00:07:57.480 --> 00:07:59.656
But shouldn't we check. to be safe?

110
00:07:59.680 --> 00:08:01.376
Get it decrypted?

111
00:08:01.400 --> 00:08:04.016
Can't. Not without the key.

112
00:08:04.040 --> 00:08:08.736
Surely GCHQ can crack encryption
without a key.

113
00:08:08.760 --> 00:08:10.560
Isn't that what we do here?

114
00:08:12.080 --> 00:08:14.496
It's part of what we do.

115
00:08:14.520 --> 00:08:16.336
So. who does that?

116
00:08:16.360 --> 00:08:18.256
The mathematicians.

117
00:08:18.280 --> 00:08:20.056
But you'd be wasting your time.

118
00:08:20.080 --> 00:08:21.360
Why?

119
00:08:22.680 --> 00:08:26.536
Sorry. I just want to understand.
for the future.

120
00:08:26.560 --> 00:08:28.936
Because it would be
a huge commitment of resources.

121
00:08:28.960 --> 00:08:31.336
and they wouldn't think it was worth it.

122
00:08:31.360 --> 00:08:33.816
Just for this little bit of encrypted text?

123
00:08:33.840 --> 00:08:35.296
That's right.

124
00:08:35.320 --> 00:08:37.336
OK. thanks for explaining.

125
00:08:37.360 --> 00:08:39.040
No problem.

126
00:08:42.960 --> 00:08:45.496
But. if I happened
to know a mathematician.

127
00:08:45.520 --> 00:08:48.176
here. in the building. would you mind?

128
00:08:48.200 --> 00:08:50.576
If I could persuade him to take a look.

129
00:08:50.600 --> 00:08:53.136
No. but he won't. And he'd be right.

130
00:08:53.160 --> 00:08:54.736
It's not a priority.

131
00:08:54.760 --> 00:08:57.080
And it's not what we've asked you to do.

132
00:09:19.640 --> 00:09:21.080
Can I take this chair?

133
00:09:31.680 --> 00:09:33.080
Thank you.

134
00:09:44.120 --> 00:09:46.960
Don't people hate having
their grammar corrected?

135
00:09:49.240 --> 00:09:51.560
Doesn't it just make everyone hate you?

136
00:09:53.120 --> 00:09:55.976
If we wrote code
as sloppily as we write English.

137
00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:57.376
it would never run.

138
00:09:57.400 --> 00:10:00.480
Some things... Some things
have to be right.

139
00:10:05.560 --> 00:10:07.560
Is that all you're having?

140
00:10:11.440 --> 00:10:13.096
I'm Muslim.

141
00:10:13.120 --> 00:10:15.496
They don't have anything halal here.

142
00:10:15.520 --> 00:10:17.560
And I don't like vegetables.

143
00:10:19.800 --> 00:10:23.800
I'm looking for a mathematician
friend. but he isn't here.

144
00:10:25.400 --> 00:10:30.296
Can you tell me where they work.
the mathematicians?

145
00:10:30.320 --> 00:10:32.200
I'm new here.

146
00:10:34.680 --> 00:10:36.736
I'll show you if you like.

147
00:10:36.760 --> 00:10:40.120
But I warn you. they won't be
very welcoming.

148
00:10:41.840 --> 00:10:43.496
What's funny?

149
00:10:43.520 --> 00:10:45.456
They won't be very welcoming?

150
00:10:45.480 --> 00:10:48.216
No different to any other department
here then?

151
00:10:48.240 --> 00:10:50.616
No different FROM
any other department.

152
00:10:50.640 --> 00:10:53.800
It's "different from". "compared with".

153
00:10:57.680 --> 00:11:00.056
Have you worked here a long time?

154
00:11:00.080 --> 00:11:02.256
Here and before.

155
00:11:02.280 --> 00:11:06.760
Before? Before we were in this.
this... doughnut.

156
00:11:09.280 --> 00:11:12.576
Was it very... different from now?

157
00:11:12.600 --> 00:11:13.960
It was.

158
00:11:17.080 --> 00:11:18.960
I'd like to have seen that.

159
00:11:24.040 --> 00:11:26.240
I can show you. if you like.

160
00:11:28.320 --> 00:11:29.736
OK.

161
00:11:29.760 --> 00:11:31.896
You wanted to see the mathematicians.

162
00:11:31.920 --> 00:11:34.520
This is it. Cryptology.

163
00:11:40.400 --> 00:11:43.936
By the way. we don't ask where
departments are at GCHQ.

164
00:11:43.960 --> 00:11:46.456
especially Cryptology.

165
00:11:46.480 --> 00:11:48.416
You know.

166
00:11:48.440 --> 00:11:51.680
security and... all that.

167
00:11:53.160 --> 00:11:55.400
But I won't tell if you don't.

168
00:11:58.280 --> 00:12:02.080
If you do want to see the old HQ.
let me know.

169
00:12:15.960 --> 00:12:19.336
Hello. I'm sorry to interrupt.

170
00:12:19.360 --> 00:12:21.960
Is there anyone here called Gabriel?

171
00:12:26.560 --> 00:12:28.656
What do you want?

172
00:12:28.680 --> 00:12:29.920
I'm busy.

173
00:12:43.840 --> 00:12:46.216
Do you really still use this stuff?

174
00:12:46.240 --> 00:12:48.136
We don't have whiteboards.

175
00:12:48.160 --> 00:12:49.680
Too noisy.

176
00:12:51.400 --> 00:12:53.120
You shouldn't be here.

177
00:13:03.560 --> 00:13:05.176
What is it?

178
00:13:05.200 --> 00:13:08.816
It's encrypted text.
from a malware string.

179
00:13:08.840 --> 00:13:12.336
Encrypted strings pop up all
the time. It doesn't mean anything.

180
00:13:12.360 --> 00:13:14.640
That's what they told me you'd say.

181
00:13:18.200 --> 00:13:20.136
Come on. Gabriel.

182
00:13:20.160 --> 00:13:23.936
Encrypted text from a piece of
malware we haven't seen before.

183
00:13:23.960 --> 00:13:27.280
It must be worth a look. surely?

184
00:13:34.440 --> 00:13:35.640
Please.

185
00:13:39.040 --> 00:13:41.256
I can't make any promises.

186
00:13:41.280 --> 00:13:45.016
We're busy. We may decide it's not
worth the time and resources.

187
00:13:45.040 --> 00:13:46.736
Are you saying you can't do it?

188
00:13:46.760 --> 00:13:47.736
No.

189
00:13:47.760 --> 00:13:50.040
I'm saying it may not be worth
the time and resources.

190
00:13:54.200 --> 00:13:55.480
Thank you.

191
00:13:59.440 --> 00:14:00.920
White boards...

192
00:14:02.120 --> 00:14:05.336
Too noisy. as in too bright. right?

193
00:14:05.360 --> 00:14:06.976
Of course.

194
00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:09.120
What else could it mean?

195
00:14:24.600 --> 00:14:26.096
Allah.

196
00:14:26.120 --> 00:14:27.696
Forgive Ahmed Parvin.

197
00:14:27.720 --> 00:14:31.216
and elevate his station
amongst those who are guided.

198
00:14:31.240 --> 00:14:34.656
Send him along the path
of those who came before.

199
00:14:34.680 --> 00:14:37.736
And forgive him and have mercy on him.

200
00:14:37.760 --> 00:14:41.376
And make him steadfast
and pardon him.

201
00:14:41.400 --> 00:14:42.936
Be generous to him.

202
00:14:42.960 --> 00:14:45.616
and cleanse him of his transgressions.

203
00:14:45.640 --> 00:14:48.376
as a white cloth cleansed of stains.

204
00:14:48.400 --> 00:14:50.720
Ameen. Ameen.

205
00:15:17.040 --> 00:15:18.176
Saara...

206
00:15:18.200 --> 00:15:19.520
Saara. no.

207
00:15:21.560 --> 00:15:22.800
Come.

208
00:15:32.120 --> 00:15:33.800
Bye-bye. Abu.

209
00:15:48.200 --> 00:15:51.680
Hello. we're going to need
to search your bag. Sure. Harriet.

210
00:15:57.040 --> 00:15:59.040
Save the planet!

211
00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:24.520
James.

212
00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:27.480
How. was it?

213
00:16:28.840 --> 00:16:30.680
No. Come here.

214
00:16:32.520 --> 00:16:34.880
Don't. please.

215
00:16:38.320 --> 00:16:40.120
Lunch is served.

216
00:16:44.800 --> 00:16:47.656
OK. anyone saying... thank you?

217
00:16:47.680 --> 00:16:51.800
Thank you? Thank you?
Thank you! Thank you. thank you.

218
00:16:57.760 --> 00:16:59.240
What's wrong?

219
00:17:01.160 --> 00:17:04.240
Are you allowed
to bring your class here?

220
00:17:06.640 --> 00:17:08.520
Am I allowed?

221
00:17:09.960 --> 00:17:11.400
Am I allowed?

222
00:17:14.280 --> 00:17:15.880
It's the weekend.

223
00:17:17.360 --> 00:17:20.336
I think it's. you know. I think it's good

224
00:17:20.360 --> 00:17:22.840
that they know what's
going on in the world.

225
00:17:24.520 --> 00:17:26.000
Isn't it?

226
00:17:29.960 --> 00:17:31.640
Is this it?

227
00:17:33.400 --> 00:17:36.016
Three words and some hexadecimal?

228
00:17:36.040 --> 00:17:38.096
Why? Were you expecting more?

229
00:17:38.120 --> 00:17:41.200
No. I don't know.

230
00:17:42.600 --> 00:17:45.696
It's just... You've done it so quickly.

231
00:17:45.720 --> 00:17:47.936
It was weird.

232
00:17:47.960 --> 00:17:49.560
What?

233
00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:53.536
You've heard of trap door encryption?

234
00:17:53.560 --> 00:17:55.976
Is that what they used?

235
00:17:56.000 --> 00:18:00.256
There was a rope hanging down.
through the trap door.

236
00:18:00.280 --> 00:18:03.320
like it wanted me to climb up it.
like it wanted to be decrypted.

237
00:18:04.480 --> 00:18:05.720
And?

238
00:18:07.720 --> 00:18:09.416
Eagles summer stages.

239
00:18:09.440 --> 00:18:10.856
that's what it says.

240
00:18:10.880 --> 00:18:13.216
Plus some hexadecimal.

241
00:18:13.240 --> 00:18:15.696
What does it mean?

242
00:18:15.720 --> 00:18:16.976
I don't know.

243
00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:19.576
And whatever you're up to.
I don't want to be involved.

244
00:18:19.600 --> 00:18:21.040
Ever.

245
00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:47.960
OK. Finn. let it loose.

246
00:19:15.720 --> 00:19:17.176
Well done.

247
00:19:17.200 --> 00:19:19.080
Now we wait.

248
00:20:54.320 --> 00:20:56.536
I think the hexadecimal's
a date and time.

249
00:20:56.560 --> 00:20:59.160
I wondered if the words
meant anything to you.

250
00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:03.520
Where did you find this?

251
00:21:05.800 --> 00:21:07.576
Hidden in the malware strings.

252
00:21:07.600 --> 00:21:10.920
I got one of the mathematicians
to decrypt it for me.

253
00:21:11.960 --> 00:21:15.696
Saara. you know that you shouldn't
be talking to me about this. right?

254
00:21:15.720 --> 00:21:18.096
I'm not cleared for
the things that you're working on.

255
00:21:18.120 --> 00:21:21.640
I know. but I just need a bit of help.

256
00:21:25.640 --> 00:21:26.800
Sit.

257
00:21:37.120 --> 00:21:38.440
I already did this.

258
00:21:39.680 --> 00:21:41.096
OK.

259
00:21:41.120 --> 00:21:44.040
Have you tried What Three Words?

260
00:21:45.360 --> 00:21:48.616
So. three apparently random words
can be used to identify

261
00:21:48.640 --> 00:21:51.080
a three-metre square
anywhere on the planet.

262
00:21:52.280 --> 00:21:57.200
Your three words are inside...
Harrogate Conference Centre.

263
00:22:00.040 --> 00:22:01.336
You said that you had a date?

264
00:22:01.360 --> 00:22:05.800
Er. 28th of April. 9:30am.

265
00:22:09.760 --> 00:22:11.616
My God.

266
00:22:11.640 --> 00:22:13.536
It's Cyber World.

267
00:22:13.560 --> 00:22:17.216
It's right in the middle
of the Cyber World conference.

268
00:22:17.240 --> 00:22:19.640
That can't be a coincidence.

269
00:22:21.080 --> 00:22:23.376
What does this mean?
I don't understand.

270
00:22:23.400 --> 00:22:26.176
You said that this was encrypted
inside the BT malware?

271
00:22:26.200 --> 00:22:27.536
Yeah.

272
00:22:27.560 --> 00:22:31.936
Well. you have a date.
a time and a place.

273
00:22:31.960 --> 00:22:35.200
It looks like someone's
sending us an invitation.

274
00:22:47.440 --> 00:22:49.456
I think it's one of their coders.

275
00:22:49.480 --> 00:22:51.200
trying to reach out.

276
00:22:55.960 --> 00:22:58.000
What do Max and Phil think about this?

277
00:23:00.800 --> 00:23:02.896
I haven't told them.

278
00:23:02.920 --> 00:23:05.096
I wanted to crack it first.

279
00:23:05.120 --> 00:23:07.056
Sorry. just to be clear.

280
00:23:07.080 --> 00:23:08.776
you're working in malware.

281
00:23:08.800 --> 00:23:11.616
and you haven't told your Head
of Department what you're doing?

282
00:23:11.640 --> 00:23:13.856
Phil agreed to me getting it decrypted.

283
00:23:13.880 --> 00:23:16.816
Yes. but you haven't told them
what you've found?

284
00:23:16.840 --> 00:23:19.120
You've gone over their heads to me?

285
00:23:21.720 --> 00:23:23.560
You're on a work placement.

286
00:23:24.920 --> 00:23:27.256
Apart from anything else. have
you considered how incredibly

287
00:23:27.280 --> 00:23:29.200
disrespectful it is to Max and Phil?

288
00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:32.840
No. truthfully. I hadn't.

289
00:23:34.560 --> 00:23:36.160
What's your involvement in this?

290
00:23:38.240 --> 00:23:41.456
Well. you know. we've been trying
to track down the coders.

291
00:23:41.480 --> 00:23:44.160
and if this is a message
from one of them...

292
00:23:52.560 --> 00:23:54.736
OK. what do you suggest we do about it?

293
00:23:54.760 --> 00:23:56.056
Me?

294
00:23:56.080 --> 00:23:57.560
Yes. you.

295
00:23:59.320 --> 00:24:01.816
I think someone should go to Harrogate.

296
00:24:01.840 --> 00:24:03.720
Me. if no-one else will.

297
00:24:09.560 --> 00:24:11.056
OK.

298
00:24:11.080 --> 00:24:12.456
OK?

299
00:24:12.480 --> 00:24:13.960
You can go.

300
00:24:16.680 --> 00:24:17.800
No way!

301
00:24:20.280 --> 00:24:21.696
I want you to go with her. OK?

302
00:24:21.720 --> 00:24:24.896
If it's Cyber World.
the FSB are gonna be there.

303
00:24:24.920 --> 00:24:26.616
It's likely one of their provocations.

304
00:24:26.640 --> 00:24:27.816
It's got all the hallmarks.

305
00:24:27.840 --> 00:24:30.640
And make sure you update Max and Phil.

306
00:24:49.920 --> 00:24:52.600
She probably thinks we're on a date.

307
00:24:54.160 --> 00:24:55.680
Or that I'm your carer.

308
00:25:10.960 --> 00:25:13.136
It's back up. Glavset.

309
00:25:13.160 --> 00:25:14.376
Yeah. Afraid so.

310
00:25:14.400 --> 00:25:17.856
So how long did we manage
to take them down for?

311
00:25:17.880 --> 00:25:19.656
About 21 hours.

312
00:25:19.680 --> 00:25:21.336
Unbelievable.

313
00:25:21.360 --> 00:25:24.376
And still no sign of a reprisal?

314
00:25:24.400 --> 00:25:27.296
No. nothing. not even a polite complaint.

315
00:25:27.320 --> 00:25:29.536
Makes us look a bit foolish. doesn't it?

316
00:25:29.560 --> 00:25:32.376
All our dire warnings about the
escalatory nature

317
00:25:32.400 --> 00:25:33.736
of offensive cyber.

318
00:25:33.760 --> 00:25:36.416
I don't know. Maybe we were
smarter than we realised.

319
00:25:36.440 --> 00:25:39.216
Russia's never acknowledged
the existence of Glavset.

320
00:25:39.240 --> 00:25:40.936
How can you complain about an attack.

321
00:25:40.960 --> 00:25:43.800
On an organisation that doesn't
officially exist?

322
00:26:20.480 --> 00:26:22.376
What was this?

323
00:26:22.400 --> 00:26:23.880
Canteen.

324
00:26:36.600 --> 00:26:40.656
And... no meat. because you don't...

325
00:26:40.680 --> 00:26:42.096
You know.

326
00:26:42.120 --> 00:26:44.080
Thank you.

327
00:26:49.440 --> 00:26:53.976
Why did you... Why did you choose
to work here in the first place?

328
00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:56.576
Here at GCHQ?

329
00:26:56.600 --> 00:26:58.760
Mum and Dad worked here.

330
00:27:00.320 --> 00:27:03.976
GCHQ's a family business.
always has been.

331
00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:05.576
So they met here?

332
00:27:05.600 --> 00:27:07.056
Here? No.

333
00:27:07.080 --> 00:27:10.056
At Bletchley. during the war.

334
00:27:10.080 --> 00:27:12.096
Hut six.

335
00:27:12.120 --> 00:27:14.216
Really?

336
00:27:14.240 --> 00:27:17.816
Yes. if it weren't for GCHQ.

337
00:27:17.840 --> 00:27:19.480
I wouldn't exist.

338
00:27:27.440 --> 00:27:30.080
I haven't told my family where I work.

339
00:27:31.440 --> 00:27:32.696
Really?

340
00:27:32.720 --> 00:27:34.416
You can now. I think.

341
00:27:34.440 --> 00:27:37.360
I know. but they wouldn't understand.

342
00:27:38.520 --> 00:27:40.920
Well. my dad did. but he died.

343
00:27:46.440 --> 00:27:48.400
You remind me of him.

344
00:28:04.720 --> 00:28:07.616
Course. back in the day.
we didn't have emails

345
00:28:07.640 --> 00:28:09.136
or bloody iPhones.

346
00:28:09.160 --> 00:28:10.856
We had Lamson tubes.

347
00:28:10.880 --> 00:28:12.400
What's that?

348
00:28:14.640 --> 00:28:17.816
An old network of pneumatic tubes.

349
00:28:17.840 --> 00:28:19.399
all over the place.

350
00:28:21.320 --> 00:28:23.896
Did you know.
if you wanted to send a document.

351
00:28:23.920 --> 00:28:25.616
do you know what you did with it?

352
00:28:25.640 --> 00:28:27.600
You rolled it up...

353
00:28:29.160 --> 00:28:31.096
put it in a carrier.

354
00:28:31.120 --> 00:28:33.896
It could be anywhere.
anywhere in all these buildings

355
00:28:33.920 --> 00:28:35.656
in two minutes. tops.

356
00:28:35.680 --> 00:28:37.176
Marvellous.

357
00:28:37.200 --> 00:28:42.720
Absolute marvellous...
piece of engineering. really.

358
00:28:45.600 --> 00:28:47.616
It was about the size of that can.

359
00:28:47.640 --> 00:28:50.936
Perfect for chocolate eclairs.

360
00:28:50.960 --> 00:28:52.456
Yeah?

361
00:28:52.480 --> 00:28:53.616
Yes.

362
00:28:53.640 --> 00:28:56.376
Stern memos were sent.

363
00:28:56.400 --> 00:29:02.800
"Personal use of the Lamson tube
is not permitted."

364
00:29:06.680 --> 00:29:09.816
It was how I proposed to my wife.

365
00:29:09.840 --> 00:29:11.536
No way.

366
00:29:11.560 --> 00:29:13.296
Did she reply?

367
00:29:13.320 --> 00:29:17.056
She said she'd think about it.

368
00:29:17.080 --> 00:29:20.336
So you didn't go down
on bended knee then?

369
00:29:20.360 --> 00:29:22.776
No. no. I was...

370
00:29:22.800 --> 00:29:25.376
far. far too shy.

371
00:29:25.400 --> 00:29:27.600
Do you...? No. You don't. do you?

372
00:29:53.040 --> 00:29:55.216
It didn't last. of course.

373
00:29:55.240 --> 00:29:56.416
She left me.

374
00:29:56.440 --> 00:29:57.720
I don't blame her.

375
00:30:00.480 --> 00:30:04.440
We could never really talk about
anything. what we were doing.

376
00:30:06.200 --> 00:30:07.840
But you both worked here?

377
00:30:09.200 --> 00:30:13.096
Surely she was the only type
of person you could talk to?

378
00:30:13.120 --> 00:30:15.256
Different departments.

379
00:30:15.280 --> 00:30:19.256
Compartmentation. they call it.

380
00:30:19.280 --> 00:30:22.520
Can't talk about what you're doing.

381
00:30:25.800 --> 00:30:28.120
Destroys relationships.

382
00:30:31.320 --> 00:30:33.120
If you're not careful.

383
00:30:37.920 --> 00:30:42.480
Funny. I used to think
of people here as my family.

384
00:30:46.160 --> 00:30:48.600
They seemed like family.

385
00:30:51.160 --> 00:30:52.640
But they weren't.

386
00:30:57.480 --> 00:30:59.000
Not my real family.

387
00:31:01.680 --> 00:31:03.920
You have to take care of your real family.

388
00:31:15.400 --> 00:31:16.640
Choose.

389
00:31:27.960 --> 00:31:29.520
James?

390
00:31:45.360 --> 00:31:46.696
Katy?

391
00:31:46.720 --> 00:31:49.136
Hi. Hi. Do you know where James is?

392
00:31:49.160 --> 00:31:52.200
Yeah. yeah. He's behind the band.
round the corner there.

393
00:31:59.600 --> 00:32:01.216
Are you Saara?

394
00:32:01.240 --> 00:32:03.696
Yeah. Is James here?

395
00:32:03.720 --> 00:32:05.280
Come on in.

396
00:32:32.600 --> 00:32:33.976
Where's your coat?

397
00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:35.440
What were you doing?

398
00:32:37.240 --> 00:32:40.000
We were just training.
for if we get arrested.

399
00:32:43.800 --> 00:32:45.160
OK. Er...

400
00:32:46.240 --> 00:32:48.696
What is it. Saara? What's the problem?

401
00:32:48.720 --> 00:32:51.280
I'm worried about your job.

402
00:32:53.240 --> 00:32:56.536
OK... It's an illegal protest and
you're bringing your class here.

403
00:32:56.560 --> 00:32:58.296
Does the school know?

404
00:32:58.320 --> 00:33:01.360
You're not a student any more. James.

405
00:33:04.240 --> 00:33:06.000
I know I'm not a student...

406
00:33:07.880 --> 00:33:11.240
any more. but are you sure it's
not your job we're talking about here?

407
00:33:15.160 --> 00:33:18.136
Yeah. Yeah. that's part of it. OK.

408
00:33:18.160 --> 00:33:21.056
Did you know that most of the
questions I got asked

409
00:33:21.080 --> 00:33:23.136
at my vetting interview were about you.

410
00:33:23.160 --> 00:33:25.320
your politics.

411
00:33:26.760 --> 00:33:28.496
Are you trying to get me into trouble?

412
00:33:28.520 --> 00:33:29.616
No!

413
00:33:29.640 --> 00:33:31.800
No. of course not.

414
00:33:35.800 --> 00:33:37.056
But what are you saying?

415
00:33:37.080 --> 00:33:39.280
That you can't work there
and have political views?

416
00:33:43.960 --> 00:33:47.680
Because I don't know about you.
but I think this is quite important.

417
00:33:49.240 --> 00:33:52.096
Whether the kids that I teach
will have a future on this planet.

418
00:33:52.120 --> 00:33:54.376
Whether the kids you and I
might have one day

419
00:33:54.400 --> 00:33:55.576
will have a future on this planet.

420
00:33:55.600 --> 00:33:57.936
Isn't that more important than your job?

421
00:33:57.960 --> 00:34:01.040
Or my job? Or any job. actually?

422
00:34:05.400 --> 00:34:06.800
What is it?

423
00:34:10.560 --> 00:34:11.960
I'm...

424
00:34:15.280 --> 00:34:18.880
I'm really not thinking
about having kids with you. James.

425
00:34:21.760 --> 00:34:24.160
I'm not. I'm sorry.

426
00:34:31.200 --> 00:34:35.736
So. the "surface of revolution"...

427
00:34:35.760 --> 00:34:40.256
is a surface... defined

428
00:34:40.280 --> 00:34:45.016
by Z equals capital H

429
00:34:45.040 --> 00:34:48.096
of R... You need to underline that.

430
00:34:48.120 --> 00:34:50.640
Where R. Z and Theta are...?

431
00:34:51.840 --> 00:34:53.040
Anyone?

432
00:34:54.400 --> 00:34:56.496
Cylindrical polar coordinates.

433
00:34:56.520 --> 00:34:58.416
Thank you. Saara.

434
00:34:58.440 --> 00:35:00.680
Well. I'm glad someone's listening.

435
00:35:04.240 --> 00:35:11.056
So. yes. our cylindrical
polar coordinates...

436
00:35:11.080 --> 00:35:16.016
So. yes. So. Z is the height co-ordinate...

437
00:35:16.040 --> 00:35:20.096
He should've written it out
before the lesson!

438
00:35:20.120 --> 00:35:21.856
He definitely likes you.

439
00:35:21.880 --> 00:35:23.896
Why don't you ask him out?

440
00:35:23.920 --> 00:35:25.496
What?

441
00:35:25.520 --> 00:35:28.320
That's so gross. Vadim.

442
00:35:32.480 --> 00:35:35.736
Anyway. I can't. He's on the faculty.

443
00:35:35.760 --> 00:35:39.240
Ask him anyway. Life's too short.

444
00:35:54.880 --> 00:35:57.200
That was good today. Yeah.

445
00:36:07.600 --> 00:36:10.296
Can I offer you a leaflet
for the Conservative Party?

446
00:36:10.320 --> 00:36:11.896
Can I offer you a leaflet?

447
00:36:11.920 --> 00:36:13.880
It's the safe vote.

448
00:36:16.200 --> 00:36:19.376
Would you like a mask?
We've got red ones. yellow ones?

449
00:36:19.400 --> 00:36:21.056
Thanks.

450
00:36:21.080 --> 00:36:22.856
For my partner.

451
00:36:22.880 --> 00:36:25.040
So who are you voting for?

452
00:36:26.440 --> 00:36:27.760
Ha-ha.

453
00:36:29.960 --> 00:36:31.256
Thanks.

454
00:36:31.280 --> 00:36:32.920
You're welcome.

455
00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:52.160
Georgia Henderson? GCHQ don't
like us to use our real names.

456
00:36:55.600 --> 00:36:56.800
OK.

457
00:36:58.040 --> 00:37:01.320
Well. let's find the place.
so we're all set for tomorrow.

458
00:37:14.440 --> 00:37:16.816
Here? Really?

459
00:37:16.840 --> 00:37:17.840
Yeah.

460
00:37:28.040 --> 00:37:29.960
Do you wanna decompress?

461
00:37:32.120 --> 00:37:33.320
Sure.

462
00:37:41.520 --> 00:37:43.856
Don't judge me. all right?

463
00:37:43.880 --> 00:37:45.976
It's a problem. I'm not.

464
00:37:46.000 --> 00:37:49.296
I've actually always wished
I was a messy person.

465
00:37:49.320 --> 00:37:53.616
What? You know. my ex's apartment
was this beautiful.

466
00:37:53.640 --> 00:37:57.336
minimalist nightmare
and if I left anything of mine out.

467
00:37:57.360 --> 00:37:59.816
she had it gone in. like. nano-seconds.

468
00:37:59.840 --> 00:38:01.776
Sounds passive aggressive to me.

469
00:38:01.800 --> 00:38:03.879
Tidying away the evidence
of your existence.

470
00:38:06.400 --> 00:38:08.840
You know what? You are exactly right.

471
00:38:12.360 --> 00:38:14.840
You're more perceptive
than I give you credit for.

472
00:38:17.160 --> 00:38:19.080
Can I have one?

473
00:38:20.120 --> 00:38:21.816
I thought you don't drink?

474
00:38:21.840 --> 00:38:23.400
I don't.

475
00:38:36.720 --> 00:38:38.496
Careful now.

476
00:38:38.520 --> 00:38:39.960
Shut up.

477
00:38:47.040 --> 00:38:49.056
Right on time.

478
00:38:49.080 --> 00:38:50.936
Dad.

479
00:38:50.960 --> 00:38:53.880
Yeah. I know. I know. I was at dinner.

480
00:38:55.560 --> 00:38:58.416
No. I did not have
a Yorkshire pudding. Dad.

481
00:38:58.440 --> 00:39:00.096
but good job on the research.

482
00:39:00.120 --> 00:39:01.520
Maybe next time.

483
00:39:03.880 --> 00:39:06.120
Look. I gotta go. OK?

484
00:39:12.440 --> 00:39:13.776
Yeah.

485
00:39:13.800 --> 00:39:15.040
Night. Dad.

486
00:39:17.520 --> 00:39:18.760
Love you too.

487
00:39:23.400 --> 00:39:24.576
Sorry about that.

488
00:39:24.600 --> 00:39:26.816
He always gets through to me.

489
00:39:26.840 --> 00:39:28.840
even when I was in Iraq.

490
00:39:32.360 --> 00:39:33.960
Have I said something wrong?

491
00:39:35.800 --> 00:39:37.440
No. No.

492
00:39:42.400 --> 00:39:44.000
Tell me.

493
00:39:48.240 --> 00:39:49.760
It's just...

494
00:39:52.640 --> 00:39:56.736
my dad died. Recently. actually.

495
00:39:56.760 --> 00:40:00.656
Fuck. I'm so sorry. Saara.
I'm such a dick...

496
00:40:00.680 --> 00:40:02.896
No. Honestly. it's fine.

497
00:40:02.920 --> 00:40:06.080
It's great you've got such a good
relationship with your dad.

498
00:40:09.280 --> 00:40:11.360
There was an accident...

499
00:40:12.840 --> 00:40:14.400
a few days ago.

500
00:40:16.480 --> 00:40:18.216
He was a train driver.

501
00:40:18.240 --> 00:40:21.256
He was on the tracks
and he was hit by a train.

502
00:40:21.280 --> 00:40:22.816
Fuck.

503
00:40:22.840 --> 00:40:25.200
That's according to my family anyway.

504
00:40:26.680 --> 00:40:29.480
What. you think that
it might have been deliberate?

505
00:40:36.240 --> 00:40:37.640
He was difficult.

506
00:40:41.280 --> 00:40:43.680
Unusual. not difficult.

507
00:40:46.760 --> 00:40:49.840
I was the only one
who really understood him.

508
00:40:52.440 --> 00:40:54.216
He was dependent on me.

509
00:40:54.240 --> 00:40:56.400
Quite heavily dependent.

510
00:40:58.440 --> 00:41:02.256
He had bouts of depression
when I was growing up.

511
00:41:02.280 --> 00:41:05.296
And I used to be the one
who could make him laugh.

512
00:41:05.320 --> 00:41:07.440
get him out of a slump.

513
00:41:10.400 --> 00:41:13.640
And I went away
and I just abandoned him.

514
00:41:15.000 --> 00:41:16.160
Hey.

515
00:41:18.560 --> 00:41:20.840
It's not your fault. OK?

516
00:41:22.280 --> 00:41:24.096
My dad's a cop.

517
00:41:24.120 --> 00:41:27.216
and he was under the towers on 9/11.

518
00:41:27.240 --> 00:41:30.376
And he lost most of his friends.

519
00:41:30.400 --> 00:41:33.400
Guys that he'd known since school.

520
00:41:34.960 --> 00:41:37.320
He was really fucked up by it.

521
00:41:38.560 --> 00:41:40.456
I mean. we all were.

522
00:41:40.480 --> 00:41:43.296
and he needed support too.

523
00:41:43.320 --> 00:41:47.856
but. in the end. I still went
away. Saara. I still...

524
00:41:47.880 --> 00:41:49.760
I still got on with my life.

525
00:41:50.960 --> 00:41:52.856
But you talk to him every day.

526
00:41:52.880 --> 00:41:55.440
even when you were in fucking Iraq.

527
00:41:57.240 --> 00:41:58.600
I ignored mine.

528
00:42:00.640 --> 00:42:02.376
I cut him out.

529
00:42:02.400 --> 00:42:03.840
Saara. he loved you.

530
00:42:05.160 --> 00:42:08.800
He loved you.
and I'm sure he understood.

531
00:42:10.280 --> 00:42:12.536
Yeah. you're right.

532
00:42:12.560 --> 00:42:16.120
He understood perfectly. that's the point.

533
00:42:17.520 --> 00:42:19.880
He threw himself under a train. Kathy.

534
00:42:37.920 --> 00:42:40.240
It's gonna be all right.

535
00:42:41.760 --> 00:42:43.880
You're gonna be all right.

536
00:43:11.360 --> 00:43:14.000
It's not... It's not a good idea.

537
00:43:15.760 --> 00:43:17.160
You're upset.

538
00:43:21.600 --> 00:43:23.120
I should go to bed.

539
00:43:28.960 --> 00:43:30.616
Yeah. me too.

540
